1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,181
Large Language Models, or LLMs, are increasingly

2
00:00:03,181 --> 00:00:06,097
deployed in economics as powerful predictive

3
00:00:06,097 --> 00:00:09,411
tools. They offer a cost-effective way to generate

4
00:00:09,411 --> 00:00:12,128
synthetic responses and forecast economic

5
00:00:12,128 --> 00:00:15,310
outcomes, embedding vast amounts of information.

6
00:00:15,310 --> 00:00:18,620
However, a clear method to assess the quality and

7
00:00:18,620 --> 00:00:21,592
true value of these LLM predictions has been

8
00:00:21,592 --> 00:00:24,970
missing. We need a unifying metric to quantify the

9
00:00:24,970 --> 00:00:28,010
benefits of substituting LLMs for human data.

10
00:00:28,009 --> 00:00:31,351
This paper introduces the 'equivalent sample size'

11
00:00:31,351 --> 00:00:34,692
(ESS), a novel measure that quantifies the domain-

12
00:00:34,692 --> 00:00:37,900
specific value of LLMs in an interpretable unit:

13
00:00:37,900 --> 00:00:40,907
the amount of human data they can effectively

14
00:00:40,907 --> 00:00:41,909
substitute for.

15
00:00:41,909 --> 00:00:44,816
ESS is defined as the smallest training sample

16
00:00:44,816 --> 00:00:47,912
size required for a conventional machine learning

17
00:00:47,912 --> 00:00:50,882
model, trained on that domain-specific data, to

18
00:00:50,882 --> 00:00:53,662
match the predictive performance of a fixed,

19
00:00:53,662 --> 00:00:54,609
pretrained LLM.

20
00:00:54,609 --> 00:00:57,611
Quantifying ESS reveals that LLMs can exhibit

21
00:00:57,611 --> 00:01:00,679
substantial heterogeneity. For some prediction

22
00:01:00,679 --> 00:01:03,881
tasks, they are excellent data surrogates, while

23
00:01:03,881 --> 00:01:06,882
for others, even minimal domain-specific data

24
00:01:06,882 --> 00:01:08,550
quickly outperforms them.

25
00:01:08,549 --> 00:01:11,068
Beyond introducing this measure, the paper

26
00:01:11,068 --> 00:01:13,885
develops a robust method for estimating the ESS

27
00:01:13,885 --> 00:01:16,343
and for conducting statistical inference,

28
00:01:16,343 --> 00:01:18,921
including constructing confidence intervals

29
00:01:18,921 --> 00:01:21,200
through sequential hypothesis testing.

30
00:01:21,200 --> 00:01:24,671
The method is applied to the Panel Study of Income

31
00:01:24,671 --> 00:01:28,074
Dynamics (PSID), a long-running U.S. longitudinal

32
00:01:28,074 --> 00:01:31,476
household survey, to evaluate LLM predictions for

33
00:01:31,476 --> 00:01:33,560
a suite of economic variables.

34
00:01:33,560 --> 00:01:36,880
Our framework studies general prediction problems:

35
00:01:36,880 --> 00:01:39,935
an analyst observes a covariate vector 'X' and

36
00:01:39,935 --> 00:01:43,056
aims to predict an outcome 'Y'. The accuracy is

37
00:01:43,056 --> 00:01:45,579
measured by an expected loss function.

38
00:01:45,579 --> 00:01:48,854
The LLM-based prediction rule involves describing

39
00:01:48,854 --> 00:01:51,995
the problem in natural language to a pretrained

40
00:01:51,995 --> 00:01:55,069
LLM, whose response becomes the prediction. We

41
00:01:55,069 --> 00:01:58,076
treat this LLM rule as fixed, without domain-

42
00:01:58,076 --> 00:01:59,480
specific fine-tuning.

43
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:02,481
An example prompt might describe an individual's

44
00:02:02,481 --> 00:02:05,546
demographic and work history, then ask the LLM to

45
00:02:05,546 --> 00:02:08,235
predict their homeownership status, clearly

46
00:02:08,235 --> 00:02:11,050
specifying output formats for interpretation.

47
00:02:11,050 --> 00:02:14,053
We compare the LLM's error to a 'domain-specific

48
00:02:14,053 --> 00:02:16,807
learning' approach, where a machine learning

49
00:02:16,807 --> 00:02:19,623
algorithm is trained on increasing amounts of

50
00:02:19,623 --> 00:02:22,689
observed (X, Y) data to produce prediction rules.

51
00:02:22,689 --> 00:02:25,841
Figure 1 illustrates the equivalent sample size,

52
00:02:25,841 --> 00:02:28,796
N*, as the point where the error curve of the

53
00:02:28,796 --> 00:02:32,079
domain-specific algorithm drops below the constant

54
00:02:32,079 --> 00:02:34,639
error level of the LLM prediction rule.

55
00:02:34,639 --> 00:02:38,032
To estimate the LLM's benchmark error, e_LLM, we

56
00:02:38,032 --> 00:02:41,354
calculate its empirical performance on the full

57
00:02:41,354 --> 00:02:44,746
dataset by querying the LLM for each observation

58
00:02:44,746 --> 00:02:47,219
and averaging the resulting losses.

59
00:02:47,219 --> 00:02:50,153
The algorithm's error curve is estimated using a

60
00:02:50,153 --> 00:02:53,086
block-out cross-validation procedure, where data

61
00:02:53,086 --> 00:02:56,141
is split into disjoint training and test blocks to

62
00:02:56,141 --> 00:02:58,280
evaluate out-of-sample performance.

63
00:02:58,280 --> 00:03:01,615
Finally, a sequential hypothesis-testing procedure

64
00:03:01,615 --> 00:03:04,885
compares the algorithm and LLM performance across

65
00:03:04,885 --> 00:03:08,220
an ordered sequence of training sizes, providing a

66
00:03:08,220 --> 00:03:11,289
reliable one-sided confidence interval for N*.

67
00:03:11,289 --> 00:03:14,120
We establish the asymptotic properties of the

68
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:17,140
estimated variance, ensuring its convergence and

69
00:03:17,140 --> 00:03:19,908
demonstrating that the studentized statistic

70
00:03:19,908 --> 00:03:22,676
follows a standard normal distribution under

71
00:03:22,676 --> 00:03:25,695
specific conditions. This forms the foundational

72
00:03:25,695 --> 00:03:28,652
theoretical basis for our subsequent hypothesis

73
00:03:28,652 --> 00:03:29,029
tests.

74
00:03:29,030 --> 00:03:32,075
To construct a valid hypothesis test comparing the

75
00:03:32,075 --> 00:03:34,877
estimated risks of machine learning models and

76
00:03:34,877 --> 00:03:37,435
Large Language Models, we introduce a loss

77
00:03:37,435 --> 00:03:40,298
difference function. This approach accounts for

78
00:03:40,298 --> 00:03:43,221
correlations between models when computed on the

79
00:03:43,221 --> 00:03:45,901
same dataset, crucial for fixed-N asymptotic

80
00:03:45,901 --> 00:03:46,450
analysis.

81
00:03:46,449 --> 00:03:49,753
Our Proposition 4.1 establishes the validity of

82
00:03:49,753 --> 00:03:53,198
the studentized test statistic, Tdiff,Nk,n. Under

83
00:03:53,198 --> 00:03:56,151
stated assumptions and the null hypothesis

84
00:03:56,151 --> 00:03:59,595
boundary, this statistic asymptotically converges

85
00:03:59,595 --> 00:04:03,040
to a standard normal distribution, confirming the

86
00:04:03,040 --> 00:04:05,359
one-sided test's asymptotic size.

87
00:04:05,359 --> 00:04:08,232
As a practical alternative to exact difference

88
00:04:08,232 --> 00:04:11,292
variance, a conservative approach sums individual

89
00:04:11,292 --> 00:04:14,040
variances. This often overestimates the true

90
00:04:14,040 --> 00:04:17,163
variance due to positive correlation between model

91
00:04:17,163 --> 00:04:20,223
errors, leading to a smaller test statistic and a

92
00:04:20,223 --> 00:04:21,659
more conservative test.

93
00:04:21,659 --> 00:04:24,811
We apply our framework to the Panel Study of

94
00:04:24,811 --> 00:04:28,248
Income Dynamics (PSID), a longitudinal household

95
00:04:28,248 --> 00:04:31,327
survey. We evaluate LLM prediction for four

96
00:04:31,327 --> 00:04:34,908
outcomes: hourly wage, homeownership, smoking, and

97
00:04:34,908 --> 00:04:37,701
drinking, utilizing detailed respondent

98
00:04:37,701 --> 00:04:39,849
characteristics as covariates.

99
00:04:39,849 --> 00:04:42,909
For continuous outcomes like hourly wage, we

100
00:04:42,909 --> 00:04:46,108
employ squared-error loss and report RMSE. For

101
00:04:46,108 --> 00:04:49,585
discrete outcomes such as homeownership, drinking,

102
00:04:49,585 --> 00:04:52,992
and smoking, we use 0-1 loss, which translates to

103
00:04:52,992 --> 00:04:54,869
the misclassification rate.

104
00:04:54,869 --> 00:04:57,904
LLM predictions are generated by transforming

105
00:04:57,904 --> 00:05:01,073
covariate vectors into natural language persona

106
00:05:01,073 --> 00:05:04,377
descriptions. Critically, we do not fine-tune the

107
00:05:04,377 --> 00:05:07,749
LLM on PSID data, and implement safeguards against

108
00:05:07,749 --> 00:05:10,783
data leakage by using static models and post-

109
00:05:10,783 --> 00:05:12,199
cutoff PSID releases.

110
00:05:12,199 --> 00:05:15,212
For domain-specific learning, we benchmark LLM

111
00:05:15,212 --> 00:05:18,487
performance against two popular supervised Machine

112
00:05:18,487 --> 00:05:21,106
Learning algorithms: Lasso regression, a

113
00:05:21,106 --> 00:05:24,250
regularized linear method, and Random Forests, a

114
00:05:24,250 --> 00:05:27,263
flexible ensemble method for capturing complex

115
00:05:27,263 --> 00:05:28,179
relationships.

116
00:05:28,179 --> 00:05:31,395
We compute error curves for each ML model, showing

117
00:05:31,395 --> 00:05:34,546
test error as a function of training sample size.

118
00:05:34,546 --> 00:05:37,311
Hyperparameters are tuned via k-fold cross-

119
00:05:37,311 --> 00:05:40,269
validation for every sample size, with results

120
00:05:40,269 --> 00:05:43,099
presented through estimated error curves and

121
00:05:43,099 --> 00:05:44,449
confidence intervals.

122
00:05:44,449 --> 00:05:47,680
Our findings from Table 1 reveal substantial

123
00:05:47,680 --> 00:05:51,351
heterogeneity in LLM predictive performance across

124
00:05:51,351 --> 00:05:54,801
tasks. The equivalent sample size (ESS) of LLMs

125
00:05:54,801 --> 00:05:58,105
varies widely, underscoring the task-specific

126
00:05:58,105 --> 00:06:01,262
nature of their utility in empirical social

127
00:06:01,262 --> 00:06:01,849
science.

128
00:06:01,849 --> 00:06:04,792
The LLM demonstrates strong performance for

129
00:06:04,792 --> 00:06:08,145
homeownership prediction, achieving an equivalent

130
00:06:08,145 --> 00:06:11,224
sample size of at least 590 observations. Its

131
00:06:11,224 --> 00:06:14,440
performance for predicting drinking behavior is

132
00:06:14,440 --> 00:06:17,040
meaningful, with an ESS of at least 41

133
00:06:17,040 --> 00:06:17,929
observations.

134
00:06:17,929 --> 00:06:21,284
LLM performance deteriorates for hourly wages,

135
00:06:21,284 --> 00:06:24,492
with an equivalent sample size of only 17-20

136
00:06:24,492 --> 00:06:27,628
observations. For smoking behavior, the LLM

137
00:06:27,628 --> 00:06:30,617
provides essentially no predictive value,

138
00:06:30,617 --> 00:06:33,972
illustrating the extremes of its task-specific

139
00:06:33,972 --> 00:06:34,919
capabilities.

140
00:06:34,919 --> 00:06:38,184
Figure 3 illustrates the Root Mean Squared Error

141
00:06:38,184 --> 00:06:41,449
(RMSE) for hourly wage prediction across varying

142
00:06:41,449 --> 00:06:44,850
training sample sizes. The graph details how model

143
00:06:44,850 --> 00:06:47,571
performance changes with increased data,

144
00:06:47,571 --> 00:06:50,019
benchmarked against the LLM's error.

145
00:06:50,019 --> 00:06:52,972
Figure 4 presents the misclassification rate for

146
00:06:52,972 --> 00:06:56,047
homeownership prediction as a function of training

147
00:06:56,047 --> 00:06:59,122
sample size. This visual shows the error curve for

148
00:06:59,122 --> 00:07:01,951
domain-specific models, highlighting where LLM

149
00:07:01,951 --> 00:07:04,349
performance aligns with traditional ML.

150
00:07:04,349 --> 00:07:07,273
Figures 5 and 6 display the misclassification

151
00:07:07,273 --> 00:07:09,871
rates for drinking and smoking behaviors

152
00:07:09,871 --> 00:07:13,054
respectively. These graphs provide detailed error

153
00:07:13,054 --> 00:07:16,107
curves across different training sizes, further

154
00:07:16,107 --> 00:07:19,161
emphasizing the variability of LLM's predictive

155
00:07:19,161 --> 00:07:20,979
utility in diverse contexts.
